---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'FAQ | adaviolationcalc.com';
const description = 'Frequently asked questions about ADA violation claims, damages, filing deadlines, and the reasonable accommodation process.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <h2>What is the deadline to file an ADA employment complaint?</h2>
  <p>You must file a charge with the EEOC within 180 days of the violation (or 300 days in states with a fair employment agency). After the EEOC issues a right-to-sue letter, you have 90 days to file in federal court. Missing these deadlines typically bars your claim.</p>
  <h2>Does the ADA cover mental health conditions?</h2>
  <p>Yes. The ADA Amendments Act of 2008 broadly expanded the definition of disability. Conditions like depression, anxiety, PTSD, and ADHD routinely qualify as disabilities under the ADA when they substantially limit a major life activity.</p>
  <h2>What is a reasonable accommodation?</h2>
  <p>Any modification to a job, work environment, or work practice that allows a qualified individual with a disability to perform the essential functions of the job &mdash; as long as it doesn&rsquo;t impose undue hardship on the employer. Examples: modified schedules, remote work, reassignment, assistive technology, leave of absence.</p>
  <h2>Can I sue my employer directly without going through the EEOC?</h2>
  <p>No. For Title I (employment) claims, you must first exhaust administrative remedies by filing with the EEOC (or equivalent state agency) and receiving a right-to-sue letter before filing in court.</p>
  <h2>Are punitive damages available against a government employer?</h2>
  <p>No. Punitive damages under Title I are not available against federal, state, or local government employers. Compensatory damages and back/front pay remain available.</p>
  <h2>What is front pay?</h2>
  <p>Front pay compensates for future lost earnings when reinstatement to your former position is not feasible (e.g., the position no longer exists, or the workplace relationship is too hostile). Courts determine the appropriate period &mdash; typically 1 to 5 years depending on circumstances.</p>
  <h2>Does the ADA apply to small businesses?</h2>
  <p>Title I (employment) applies only to employers with 15 or more employees. Title III (public accommodations) applies to most businesses that serve the public regardless of size, though some small religious organizations are exempt.</p>
  <h2>What if I signed a severance agreement?</h2>
  <p>Severance agreements often include waivers of ADA claims. To be enforceable, the waiver must be knowing and voluntary, and ADEA-specific requirements (21-day consideration, 7-day revocation) apply to older workers. An employment attorney can review whether a waiver would hold.</p>
</BaseLayout>
